Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for the Next.js project.

## What was implemented:

1. **Installed @vercel/speed-insights package (v2.0.0)**
   - Used npm to install the latest version of the package
   - Package was added to dependencies in package.json

2. **Added SpeedInsights component to root layout**
   - Modified: frontend/app/layout.tsx
   - Imported SpeedInsights from '@vercel/speed-insights/next'
   - Added <SpeedInsights /> component alongside existing <Analytics /> component
   - Placed within the <body> tag as recommended by Vercel documentation

3. **Updated lock files**
   - package-lock.json was updated with new dependencies

## Framework-specific details:

This is a Next.js 16.0.10 project using the App Router pattern. Following the official Vercel documentation for Next.js v13.5+:
- Used the Next.js-specific import: '@vercel/speed-insights/next'
- Added the component to the root layout file (app/layout.tsx)
- The SpeedInsights component is a client component that will automatically track Core Web Vitals

## Implementation notes:

- The project already had Vercel Analytics installed, so Speed Insights was added alongside it
- The integration is framework-aware and will automatically capture metrics like:
  - Largest Contentful Paint (LCP)
  - First Input Delay (FID)
  - Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS)
  - First Contentful Paint (FCP)
  - Time to First Byte (TTFB)
- Build completed successfully with no errors
- TypeScript compilation passed
- All changes follow existing code patterns and structure

## Next steps:

To view Speed Insights data:
1. Deploy this code to Vercel
2. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel dashboard (if not already enabled)
3. After deployment and user visits, metrics will appear in the Speed Insights section

The implementation is complete and ready for deployment.
